# Modern Data Lake on AWS for Field Sensor Analytics

## Business Problem
Agriculture client needed to ingest 500GB/day from IoT field sensors, data partners, and manual CSV uploads. Legacy on-prem SQL Server couldn't scale. Needed self-service BI for analysts + cost <$1K/month.

## Architecture Overview
S3-based data lake with serverless ETL and analytics. Separates storage from compute for cost optimization.

![Architecture Diagram](./data lakes.png)

## Core AWS Services
| Service | Purpose |
| --- | --- |
| Amazon S3 | Data lake storage. Raw zone, processed zone, curated zone |
| AWS Glue | Crawls S3 to build Data Catalog. Runs Spark ETL jobs |
| AWS Batch | Heavy lifting: daily aggregation, ML feature engineering |
| Amazon Athena | Serverless SQL queries on S3. Analysts run ad-hoc queries |
| Amazon Redshift | Data warehouse for sub-second BI dashboards |
| Amazon QuickSight | BI dashboards for execs. Embedded in internal portal |
| AWS Lake Formation | Fine-grained column/row permissions on S3 + Glue tables |
| AWS IAM + KMS | Role-based access + S3 encryption at rest |
| AWS Config | Audits S3 bucket policies for compliance |

## Data Flow
1. Data Sources → S3 Raw Bucket: Manual uploads, partners via SFTP, sensors via Kinesis Firehose
2. Glue Crawler → discovers schema → Glue Data Catalog
3. Glue ETL Jobs + AWS Batch → clean/aggregate → S3 Processed Bucket
4. Athena queries S3 directly for data scientists. Redshift Spectrum queries S3 for BI
5. QuickSight dashboards pull from Athena/Redshift → executives view KPIs

## Security + Governance Features
1. Lake Formation: Grant SELECT on `sensor_readings` table to `analysts` group only
2. S3 Encryption: All buckets SSE-KMS. Bucket policies deny unencrypted uploads
3. IAM Roles: Glue jobs assume `GlueETLRole`, Athena users assume `AnalystRole`
4. Config Rules: `s3-bucket-public-read-prohibited` ensures no data leaks
5. Data Lineage: Glue tracks job runs → know what transformed which dataset

## Results
- Cost: $600/month vs $12K/month on-prem SQL cluster = 95% savings
- Scale: Ingests 500GB/day → 15TB/month with zero capacity planning
- Speed: Analysts query 1 year of data in Athena in <30s vs 4 hours before
- Self-Service: 20 business users build own QuickSight dashboards without IT

## Lesson Learned
1. Partition S3 by `year=/month=/day=` or Athena queries will scan everything = $$$
2. Use Glue Workflows to chain crawlers + ETL. Don’t run them manually
3. Redshift Spectrum is cheaper than loading all data into Redshift for cold queries
4. Lake Formation permissions override S3 bucket policies - test carefully
5. QuickSight SPICE imports data for <1s dashboards, but costs extra vs direct query
6. Amazon Athena provides interactive SQL queries across datasets in S3, including those produced by both Glue ETL jobs and Amazon Batch pipelines.
7. Amazon Redshift optionally integrates for high performace SQL analytics and joins across structured research datasets. It can federate with S3 using Redshift Spectrum for unified access.
8. Amazon QuickSight delivers visual dashboards for researchers and program


